{"id":"1904.11646","submitter":"Pei-Lun Tseng","authors":"Pei-Lun Tseng","title":"A Unified approach to Infinitesimal Freeness with Amalgamation","comments":"We added a new Section, regarding the linearization trick in\n  infinitesimal freeness. Also, we corrected some typos","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OA math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The linearization trick in freeness was introduced by Belinschi, Mai, and\nSpeicher. The main goal of this paper is providing the analogous linearization\nmethod in infinitesimal freeness. More precisely, we provide the solution for\nthe following problem: suppose that $A_1(N),\\dots,A_k(N)$ are self-adjoint\n$N\\times N$ random matrices which are asymptotically infinitesimally free for\n$N\\to \\infty$, let $p$ be a self-adjoint polynomial in $k$ non-commuting\nvariables and let $P_N=p(A_1(N),\\dots,A_k(N))$. Can we calculate the asymptotic\ninfinitesimal distribution of $P$ in terms of the asymptotic infinitesimal\ndistributions of $A_1(N),\\dots,A_k(N)$?\n  Firstly, we consider the infinitesimal freeness in the operator-valued\nframework, and we show that the operator-valued infinitesimal free independence\nis equivalent to the operator-valued free independence over an algebra of\n$2\\times 2$ upper triangular matrices. Then we introduce the notion of\noperator-valued infinitesimal cumulants and study its properties. We deduce\nthat the operator valued infinitesimal freeness is equivalent to the vanishing\nof our mixed cumulants. Moreover, we establish the formula to obtain the free\nadditive convolution, in the context of operator valued infinitesimal freeness.\nCombining these new results with Anderson's linearization trick, we give the\nalgorithmic solution of the above problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 Apr 2019 02:01:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 28 May 2020 20:24:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":